questions.question:
Given the following syntax directed translation rules:

Rule 1: R -> A D { B.i = R.i - 1; A.i = B.i; R.i = A.i + 1; }
Rule 2: P -> C D { P.s = C.s + D.s; D.i = C.i + 2; }
Rule 3: Q -> E F { Q.s = E.s + F.s; E.i = F.s + 1; }

Which ONE is the CORRECT option among the following?

A. Rule 1 is S-attributed and L-attributed; Rule 2 is S-attributed and not L-attributed; Rule 3 is neither S-attributed nor L-attributed.
B. Rule 1 is neither S-attributed nor L-attributed; Rule 2 is not S-attributed and is L-attributed; Rule 3 is S-attributed and L-attributed.
C. Rule 1 is neither S-attributed nor L-attributed; Rule 2 is not S-attributed and is L-attributed; Rule 3 is neither S-attributed nor L-attributed.
D. Rule 1 is S-attributed and L-attributed; Rule 2 is not S-attributed and is L-attributed; Rule 3 is neither S-attributed nor L-attributed.

Study the following program written in a block-structured language:

Var x: integer;
procedure P(n:integer);
begin
    x := n + 2*(n-3);
    P(x);
    Write(x);
end

procedure Q;
Var x: integer;
begin
    x := 7;
    P(x-2);
end

begin
    x := 2;
    Q;
    Write(x);
end

What will be printed by the write statements marked (1) and (2) in the program if the variables are statically scoped?

A. 3, 6     B. 6, 7     C. 3, 7     D. None of the above
